The most feared macro event of them all, the yield curve inversion pivot... could it finally be happening?

#Bitcoin has only seen one of these before, during the 2020 black swan.

Why are people so scared of this?

It is an extremely accurate recession predictor, and now the yield curve is more inverted than ever before, seemingly already pivoting.

What is the pivot?

This happens when the 2 year treasury yield rate starts to outpace the 10 year.

Typically, the longer yield would have a higher rate, but when shorter yields are on the rise it shows investors are flocking to long-term rates and not confident in the short term. This in many cases leads to a recession.

There are many reflections of 2008 housing market crash and the 2000s dot com bubble crash, but not all pivots cause catastrophe.

The 1998 pivot did not end in a recession, and the 90's pivot led to a very mild one.

Who knows the extent of damage to the markets this will cause, there's no way to say for sure. Let's observe.

The #Bitcoin White Paper was a marketing document to get the attention of cypher punks who had been toying around the with the idea of e-cash for some time. The use of the term "cash" was more relatable to this group than the use of the word "gold" because cypher punks were not typically gold bugs. This was a way to get their attention.

It's a mistake to treat the white paper like the only representation of Satoshi's intentions when it was clearly not fully fleshed out. I have read it. He omitted the block size, the time between blocks, and the supply cap from the white paper.

Clearly the WP was not the entire blueprint for Bitcoin. He probably spent 3 years writing code for Bitcoin, and less than one week writing the white paper. How does it make sense to only focus on the WP? We have to put more weight on the real work that Satoshi did which was writing the source code.

The source code describes a digital store of value, without any utility, and without a ton of capacity on the base layer. Finite supply encourages hodling, not spending. 10 min block times are less than ideal. And so are small blocks. None of these are optimal design decision for a spending currency. They are, however, ideal for a SoV.

Both large blockers and small blockers believe that BTC was designed to be both an MoE and a SoV. Where we differ is priority.

As a small blocker, I believe that Satoshi prioritized its Store of Value attributes because of the way he designed the protocol, and because he was smart enough to know that an emergent currency can never achieve MoE status unless it could overcome the chicken or the egg problem and build a real network of users. The only way to do that is to give people an incentive to buy and hold BTC long before it's ever useful as a medium of exchange. Why do you think all of the faster chains designed to be MoE are still lagging behind #BTC after all these years? 

If people are not incentivized to save in it, it will never reach a critical mass of users. SoV has to come first. It has always been that way with emergent money. Human nature does not change. Why would this phenomenon change? Satoshi knew this. To suggest that Satoshi would prioritize MoE first is to imply that Satoshi didn't know what he was doing. It's insulting. 

If I were wrong, then BCH and BSV would have crushed BTC, as they both fixed the scalability on layer 1. They both supposedly solved the problem that people had, right? Why are they down 99% against BTC?

The world needs a superior store of value more than it needs another fast payment option. #BTC is the very embodiment of Satoshi's vision.

These repeated narratives I come in contact with almost always lack adequate investigation and research. In other words, they are almost always spouted by either those who are too intellectually lazy to verify them or by those who are intellectually dishonest and don't want them refuted. So, I guess this one is left for me to dismantle. üßµ

Image 1 shows a relatively recent snapshot of #Bitcoin's distribution across its network. As you'll see, outside of Satoshi Nakamoto's 1 million+ BTC, there are only five other addresses that hold between 100,000 and 1 million BTC, with the total of those addresses coming in at 779,000 #BTC. This number accounts for only 3.7% of the total supply.

The next stratum up reveals that only 92 addresses hold between 10,000 and 100,000 #BTC. This category is often referred to as the domain of the whales. These whale addresses hold 2.17 million BTC collectively, and it accounts for 10.3% of the total supply.

Let's pause right here. There really is no need to go further. Let's pick apart what we have so far to see if the claim that #BTC is held in a very concentrated way holds water, as it were.

Aside from Satoshi's address(s), the top tier addresses belong to Binance, Coinbase, Bitfinex and an unknown. These companies represent and hold BTC on behalf of tens if not hundreds of millions of individual owners. This is not concentration at all. It's broad distribution in terms of ownership, although it is held or custodied in a concentrated way. That is another topic all together. 

Grayscale (GBTC) and the already established spot Bitcoin ETFs own a total of 819,000 BTC, with GBTC holding the lion's share of that number at 644,000. Again, all of this is on behalf of millions of individuals across the globe.

Publicly traded companies like Microstrategy (MSTR), Robinhood, Tesla, Digital Galaxy, Marathon, Hut 8, and the like, collectively have 254,000 BTC, about 1.2% of the total supply. Again here, these publicly traded companies are just that, holders for the "public." Micheal Saylor's MSTR owns 155,000 on behalf of 1,028 individual stock holders. This is not concentration at all. It's just group buying. 

We haven't even begun to pick apart the government holdings of #Bitcoin yet. These behemoths, theoretically at least, hold BTC on behalf of their entire citizenry. The US and China are the biggest in this category, but collectively all countries hold 245,000 BTC. By the way, how does Ukraine own more BTC than most of all the countries in the world? ü§î O.k, I digress. 

Now I know some billionaires have sizable holdings like Micheal Saylor, the Winklevi Twins and Tim Draper, but that's only four people. 

The point is this. I think most who ignorantly make the claim that #Bitcoin is too concentrated into the hands of a few miss the fact that most addresses represent the ownership of millions to hundreds of millions of individuals. I also think they fail to realize that the distribution of any money always starts off concentrated but gets more widely distributed over time, which is exactly what happened and continues to happen with BTC.  

First there was only Satoshi. That's one. Then Hal Finney. That's two. Now look. Hundreds of millions. If we revisit these numbers two months from now, you'll see even wider distribution.

#Bitcoin is available for anyone today and will ultimately be adopted by everyone. It's doing just fine, spreading itself throughout the world from its starting point, Satoshi Nakamoto. Don't worry about too much concentration. As the price advances higher and higher, so will the distribution get wider and wider.
